I"I<p>The sensory recruitment hypothesis argues that working memory is based on sustained activity in sensory areas. This theory posits that prefrontal regions are merely in charge of orchestrating working memory at a high level, while sensory areas are tasked with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/consciousness-contains-transient-latent-representations">keeping representations active</a> through various coding mechanisms. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/drawing-surfaces-extend-visuospatial-sketchpad">Drawing surfaces externalize such representations</a>.</p>
